{
  "body" : "Convert the input illustration into a luxury embossed / debossed relief artwork.\n\n— Preservation rule (CRITICAL) —\n{{preserve_composition}}. The composition, character, pose, facial features, and all recognizable elements from the original illustration must remain intact — only the rendering medium changes. Think of it as the original artwork being physically pressed into a luxury material by a master craftsman.\n\n— Material —\n{{material}}.\nThe material's surface should feel real and tangible — natural micro-texture (paper grain / metal brush marks / leather pebble / plaster grain) visible at close range. The viewer should want to reach out and touch it.\n\n— Embossing depth & technique —\n{{emboss_depth}}.\nWhere the original illustration has dark / strong elements, the surface either rises (emboss) or sinks (deboss) accordingly. Edges of raised / sunken areas show realistic press behavior — slight bevels, soft micro-shadows along the edge, occasional pressure marks. NOT a flat digital bevel filter — this must look like real physical pressing of paper or metal.\n\n— Lighting & shadow —\n{{lighting_direction}}.\nThe light is what gives the relief its life: highlights catch the raised edges, shadows pool in the recesses, and gentle gradients reveal the dimensional curvature of every form. Light should feel real and physically motivated, like a photograph of an actual relief artwork on a desk.\n\n— Color —\n{{color_treatment}}.\nMaintain restraint — embossed luxury work draws its beauty from light & shadow on a single material, not from color. If color is introduced, it appears only as a single deliberate accent (foil stamp, ink touch).\n\n— Background —\n{{background_treatment}}.\n\n— Composition framing —\nCapture the embossed work centered with respectful space around it. Show enough surrounding area for the viewer to read it as a physical object, not a flat graphic. Captured in {{aspect_ratio}}.\n\n— Mood & quality —\nTactile, luxurious, refined, contemplative, museum-quality, premium-stationery aesthetic. The kind of relief work you'd find on a high-end wedding invitation, a luxury brand's seasonal card, a Japanese artisan's letterpress studio shelf, a French couture house's embossed envelope, or a museum gift shop's collector card.\n\n— Additional details —\n{{extra_notes}}\n\n— Strictly avoid —\n- Do NOT change the composition, character, pose, or recognizable elements from the original\n- Do NOT add new objects, characters, or background scenery not present in the original\n- Do NOT use a flat digital bevel / Photoshop layer style — the relief must look physically pressed\n- Do NOT make the embossing look like a noise filter or texture overlay\n- Do NOT use Photoshop's \"Emboss\" filter aesthetic (the gray flat one)\n- Do NOT add color outside what {{color_treatment}} specifies\n- Do NOT add lens flares, glow effects, or digital embellishments\n- Do NOT make the surface look glossy / reflective like CGI plastic — it must look like real material\n- Do NOT add cute decorations, sparkles, hearts, kawaii motifs\n- Do NOT distort the relief edges aggressively — they must look clean and pressed by precision tooling\n- Do NOT rotate or skew the original — preserve orientation\n- Do NOT add watermarks, signatures, or text not present in the original\n\nKeywords: embossed luxury card, debossed cotton paper, blind deboss, letterpress, foil stamp, bas-relief, metal pressed plaque, brass relief, copper engraving, museum-quality print, tactile texture, light and shadow play, premium stationery, luxury invitation, エンボス加工, レリーフ, 浮き彫り.",
